[start section id="20113"]

#1 Recurrent rectal cancer with extensive presacral tissue involvement

[end section id="20113"]

[start section id="20101"]

Anna T. Marshall, R.N., C.N.P.

[end section id="20101"]

[start section id="20102"]

Surgical intervention for recurrent rectal cancer.

[end section id="20102"]

[start section id="20103"]

Mr. Palmer is a pleasant 57-year-old gentleman from OH who presents to Dr. Mccoy Service for the chief complaint.  He has a previous history of neoadjuvant treatment and a low-anterior resection for rectal cancer back in December 2008.  He initially did well postoperatively; however, in April of this year, he had a followup CT-scan which demonstrated some changes around his bladder.  He underwent cystoscopy, and there was some erythema noted on the bladder mucosa.  Subsequent colonoscopy in June of this year demonstrated some inflammation at the rectal anastomosis.  He ended up having biopsy-proven recurrence of his cancer.  Workup here at Walthall has unfortunately demonstrated a large presacral mass encompassing some of the sacral nerves, the anterior portion of the distal sacrum, and probable involvement of the bladder as well.  He presents to Dr. Mccoy Service and multiple other surgical specialties for hopeful surgical management of his problem.
His past medical and surgical history is outlined below.

[end section id="20103"]

[start section id="20107"]

PAST MEDICAL HISTORY
1.  Recurrent rectal cancer.
2.  History of renal stones.
3.  History of migraine headaches.
PAST SURGICAL HISTORY
1.  Hernia repair in December 2009.
2.  Colostomy reversal in March 2009.
3.  Low-anterior resection with stool diversion in December 2008.
4.  Left rotator cuff surgery.

[end section id="20107"]

[start section id="20108"]

He has been married for the past 35 years.  He has been employed as a welder and as a part-time painter.  He is a lifelong nonsmoker.  No alcohol abuse.

[end section id="20108"]

[start section id="20109"]

Negative for any GI neoplasia or inflammatory bowel disease, however, significant for mother who died of lung cancer.  His father had prostate cancer.

[end section id="20109"]

